body:
Thanks for reporting this.

The traceback is a little confusing as it is a nested panic - the original error was the panic here which is an internal error:

https://github.com/rclone/rclone/blob/da404dc0f28e919cda0b7a7176518f28a1850f91/vfs/vfscache/downloaders/downloaders.go#L103-L107

This is triggered by the code added relatively recently in ec72432cecdc4eee9abf25e3fb0119d897b5bba2 to fix a bug with renaming files

So I'm guessing that
- a file was added to the mount
- it was then renamed
- it was then opened before the original upload had completed

I tried that sequence, but it didn't reproduce the bug.

To have any hope of fixing this, I need to have either a way to reproduce the problem locally, or a log with `-vv` of the problem happening.

Can you make it happen again do you think?

I think I have the same issue. Mine isn't encrypted; but it is Google Drive. I have yt-dlp (via a web front end) running that downloads a `abc.mp4` using yt-dlp (downloads it to `abc.temp.mp4` and then it renames it to `abc.mp4` once it finishes.

The 'exec' part of yt-dlp runs a script that renames the mp4 to `.mp4.orig` and then runs a `ffmpeg` instance to create a transcoded file with the original file name (`abc.mp4`. This works ok for a while, but sometimes will cause a big panic. It's crashed at least 3 times in a similar way.

Here's the (quite long) logs: https://gist.github.com/ofifoto/155cc27513bdbb581d79e9aa836703b7 (I don't think this contains anything sensitive; @ncw  can you confirm?)

@ofifoto yes that is the same problem by the look of it. No there is nothing sensitive in that log.

That is useful info - I couldn't repro the problem yet though.

What are your mount parameters?

I'm trying with this shell script to make the problem happen - maybe you can have a go with it and adjust it until it does show the problem?

```
#!/bin/bash                                                                                                                                                                                   
                                                                                                                                                                                              
# Attempt to replicate the issue                                                                                                                                                              
                                                                                                                                                                                              
set -ex                                                                                                                                                                                       
                                                                                                                                                                                              
mnt=/mnt/tmp                                                                                                                                                                                  
file=${mnt}/file.txt                                                                                                                                                                          
                                                                                                                                                                                              
while true; do                                                                                                                                                                                
                                                                                                                                                                                              
    rm -f ${file}                                                                                                                                                                             
                                                                                                                                                                                              
    sleep 1s                                                                                                                                                                                  
                                                                                                                                                                                              
    rclone test makefile --chargen 100M $file                                                                                                                                                 
                                                                                                                                                                                              
    sleep 30s                                                                                                                                                                                 
                                                                                                                                                                                              
    mv ${file} ${file}.orig                                                                                                                                                                   
                                                                                                                                                                                              
    sleep 1s                                                                                                                                                                                  
                                                                                                                                                                                              
    cat < ${file}.orig > ${file}                                                                                                                                                              
                                                                                                                                                                                              
    sleep 10s                                                                                                                                                                                 
                                                                                                                                                                                              
    md5sum ${file}                                                                                                                                                                            
                                                                                                                                                                                              
    sleep 1s                                                                                                                                                                                  
                                                                                                                                                                                              
    rm -f ${file}.orig                                                                                                                                                                        
                                                                                                                                                                                              
    sleep 1s                                                                                                                                                                                  
                                                                                                                                                                                              
done                                                                                                                                                                                          
```

Hi! just having the same issue. I've recently configured NFS client on an Ubuntu Virtual Machine to download files from Telegram to rclone mount shared folder (vfs cache). Everything seems to look good, but after downloading several files rclone always crashes.

**EDIT:**
Here is my situation:

**Server (QNAP NAS):**

rclone share mount:

rclone mount rclonecrypt:Downloads /share/homes/rclone/Downloads/RClone --config=/share/homes/rclone/.config/rclone/rclone.conf --allow-other --bwlimit 8M --dir-cache-time 1000h --umask 002 --vfs-cache-mode writes --vfs-cache-max-age 0h0m0s --cache-dir /share/homes/rclone/Downloads/cacherclone --log-level INFO --log-file /share/homes/rclone/Downloads/rclonelog --poll-interval 15s --user-agent menjaomatic --rc-addr=localhost:5575

QNAP Shared NFS folder:

Then to be able to share by nfs the rclone mounted Google Drive in QNAP, I need to create a share folder (/share/RClone_downloads) who has defined an access route (/share/homes/rclone/Downloads/RClone) and configure the nfs access to /share/RClone_downloads folder.


**Client (Ubuntu Virtual Machine on the same QNAP NAS):**

NFS mount:
mount -t nfs4 -o vers=4.0 nas_ip:/RClone_downloads  /mnt/downloads


Everything works as expected, I can download some files from Telegram (4-5) and then rclone crashes with the "fatal error: sync: unlock of unlocked mutex".

@ncw Not a solution. However the problem is resolved and the Mount working again. I allowed the cache to finish uploading to google. Once completed, deleted the cache directory, restarted the computer and remounted with the same settings. Plex is now scanning again, and all the leftover cache files were successfully loaded to the cloud with no data loss.

I don't know what the code is doing here.. but seems like we're having the same issue under different circumstances? I'm going to update my previous post with what is happening in my case. 
I think Telegram downloads don't rename files and download the files "as they are".

Thank you very much for everything.

**EDIT:** After resetting the NAS and reconfiguring a new share I've downloaded 20 files without problems... I can't confirm that, but seems like if you download and delete a file from Google Drive it is still preserved somehow in the file system. If you download the same file you deleted before, the crash appears. So changing the dowload destination folder for the file seems to have made a difference. So.. in my case it is solved for now.

Thanks a lot!

I have attempted to fix this issue here

[v1.59.0-beta.6203.642d221dc.fix-6190-vfs-crash](https://beta.rclone.org/branch/fix-6190-vfs-crash/v1.59.0-beta.6203.642d221dc.fix-6190-vfs-crash/) on branch [fix-6190-vfs-crash](https://github.com/rclone/rclone/tree/fix-6190-vfs-crash) (uploaded in 15-30 mins)

I haven't been able to reproduce it myself so I'm not sure the fix is correct - testing much appreciated!

issue.body:

We understand you are having a problem with rclone; we want to help you with that!

**STOP and READ**
**YOUR POST WILL BE REMOVED IF IT IS LOW QUALITY**:
Please show the effort you've put into solving the problem and please be specific.
People are volunteering their time to help! Low effort posts are not likely to get good answers!

If you think you might have found a bug, try to replicate it with the latest beta (or stable).
The update instructions are available at https://rclone.org/commands/rclone_selfupdate/

If you can still replicate it or just got a question then please use the rclone forum:

    https://forum.rclone.org/

for a quick response instead of filing an issue on this repo.

If nothing else helps, then please fill in the info below which helps us help you.

**DO NOT REDACT** any information except passwords/keys/personal info.

You should use 3 backticks to begin and end your paste to make it readable.

Make sure to include a log obtained with '-vv'.

You can also use '-vv --log-file bug.log' and a service such as https://pastebin.com or https://gist.github.com/

Thank you

The Rclone Developers

-->

#### The associated forum post URL from `https://forum.rclone.org`
-


#### What is the problem you are having with rclone?
Random disconnect from mount with crash-looking output.


#### What is your rclone version (output from `rclone version`)
1.58.1


#### Which OS you are using and how many bits (e.g. Windows 7, 64 bit)
MacOS 10.14.6 [Macfuse 4.2.5 used within the Finder but it seems the crash may be within rclone?]


#### Which cloud storage system are you using? (e.g. Google Drive)
Dropbox


#### The command you were trying to run (e.g. `rclone copy /tmp remote:tmp`)
existing mount can be running for hours or days (

rclone mount DB1-ENC: ~/DB1-ENC --volname "DB1-ENC"     --drive-acknowledge-abuse     --vfs-cache-mode full --vfs-cache-max-size 10G --verbose"

#### A log from the command with the `-vv` flag (e.g. output from `rclone -vv copy /tmp remote:tmp`)
As the crash is random with no pattern (but it has happened several times) there is no log. Attached is a Pastebin to show the crashed console output. I do not think there is a problem with the rclone connection (works on another Mac as well as under Linux to the same location/same commands).

https://pastebin.com/wANSf4fW

If there is a command to log (even if it runs for days) can you advise if it is necessary at this stage? Ideally it could prune itself as it will grow very, very large in short order!

* Please don't comment if you have no relevant information to add. It's just extra noise for everyone subscribed to this issue.
* Subscribe to receive notifications on status change and new comments.

body:
I've merged this to master now which means it will be in [the latest beta](https://beta.rclone.org/) in 15-30 minutes and released in v1.59

Please let me know if it happens again.

Sorry about the lack of response! Life's been a bit of a brick lately and the email response got lost in the river. I've updated to the beta and will do testing and let you know if it happens again. Thanks for the fix!
